# Rust Development Rules

## Code Style and Formatting
- Always use `cargo fmt` for code formatting before committing
- Follow Rust naming conventions: snake_case for variables/functions, PascalCase for types
- Use rustfmt default style (100 character line width)
- Prefer explicit types when it improves readability

## Error Handling
- Always use Result<T, E> for fallible operations, never panic in library code
- Implement Error trait for custom error types
- Use `?` operator for error propagation when appropriate
- Provide meaningful error messages with context
- For errors crossing FFI boundaries (Tauri), ensure errors are Send + Sync

## Memory Safety
- Prefer borrowing (&T) over owned values (T) when possible
- Use Arc<Mutex<T>> for shared mutable state across threads
- Avoid unsafe blocks unless absolutely necessary, and document why unsafe is needed
- Use RAII patterns for resource management

## Tauri-Specific Patterns
- Use `#[tauri::command]` for exposed functions
- Return serializable types (use serde Serialize/Deserialize)
- Use async commands for I/O operations
- Handle COM initialization properly for Windows APIs
- Use `unsafe` blocks responsibly when working with Windows COM APIs

## Windows API Usage
- Always initialize COM before using COM-based APIs
- Use proper error checking for Windows API calls (HRESULT checks)
- Clean up COM objects properly (call Release() when done)
- Use windows-rs bindings, prefer safe wrappers when available
- Document unsafe blocks that interact with Windows APIs

## Testing
- Write unit tests alongside code
- Use `#[cfg(test)]` for test modules
- Test error paths as well as success paths
- Mock external dependencies when appropriate

## Dependencies
- Keep dependencies minimal and well-maintained
- Use workspace dependencies when sharing code between crates
- Document why external crates are needed

## Performance
- Prefer zero-copy operations when possible
- Use iterators instead of loops for better optimization
- Profile before optimizing
- Avoid unnecessary allocations

## Documentation
- Use /// for public API documentation
- Include examples in doc comments for complex functions
- Document safety invariants for unsafe code
- Explain non-obvious algorithms or workarounds
